ff81cf4fa499d4f094283f0d1bd5ccb72fad1dd464c571e12228" style=3D"color:#d4000=
0;text-decoration:none;font-weight:bold" class=3D"sdf">noted</a></u> that D=
=2EE.I. chief <b>Yashica</b> <b>Olden</=
b> quit this past summer following acc=
usations of antisemitism=E2=80=94in particular, some comments she made in p=
assing to Jewish employees, including expressing reticence about sending a =
Holocaust Memorial Day email last year. (Although it=E2=80=99s my understan=
ding that Duncan was <i>also</i> concerned about sending the note.)<br/><br=
/>Tani cited a December email from <i>Vogue</i> entertainment director <b>S=
ergio</b> <b>Kletnoy</b> raising concerns about <i>Teen Vogue</i>=E2=80=99s=
 allegedly pro-Palestinian Gaza coverage. As Tani noted, Cond=C3=A9 Nast em=
ployees have apparently become incredibly reluctant to bring these issues t=
o their human resources department, partly because they feel their concerns=
 are ignored. Kletnoy met with several of the seven or so company executive=
s after sending his email and
apparently came away feeling like the only person who showed sympathy for h=
is concerns was <b>Anna</b> <b>Wintour</b>. She checked in on Jewish employ=
ees after the war began and invited a concentration camp survivor to speak =
to employees in the wake of Kletnoy=E2=80=99s email.<br/><br/>Many believe =
Olden was a scapegoat for broader mistakes by the leadership team during th=
e past year. Employees have said that executives mishandled communicating a=
bout the October 7 attacks on Israel, and failed to create clear expectatio=
ns for what was, and wasn=E2=80=99t, permissible public commentary about th=
e war. Most notably, of course, contributing editor-at-large <b>Gabriella K=
arefa-Johnson</b> resigned from <i>Vogue</i> last year, shortly after the O=
ct. 7 attacks, when she compared Israel to an =E2=80=9Capartheid state=E2=
=80=9D and the Israeli military to a =E2=80=9Cterrorist organization.=E2=80=
=9D Other employees have been reprimanded by human resources for speaking o=
ut about the Israeli-Palestinian conflict, without
any follow-up guidance on what constitutes acceptable language. <br/><br/>A=
nyway, this horrible war has created complex internal dynamics for virtuall=
y every business. But the funny thing about Olden is that pretty much every=
one I spoke to believes that she was a good person who was trying to do the=
 right thing, who also made remarks that could have been construed as antis=
emitic remarks. =E2=80=9CWhat happened with Yashica wasn=E2=80=99t great,=
=E2=80=9D one person said. =E2=80=9CBut her being forced out wasn=E2=80=99t=
 the solution.=E2=80=9D (I reached out to Olden for comment on this but hav=
e yet to hear back.) <br/><br/>The company leadership team also effectively=
 undercut her by slashing her staff and budget, an unfortunate consequence =
of Cond=C3=A9=E2=80=99s revenue challenges. Like much of the grunt work at =
this company, the onus somehow fell on Wintour, the keeper of what=E2=80=99=
s left of Cond=C3=A9 Nast=E2=80=99s flame, to clean up the mess. (The compa=
ny has yet to hire a replacement for Olden.) <br/><br/>Things are destined =
to
grow more intense as autumn progresses and concerns around potential layoff=
s bubble up once again. Next Tuesday, new chief revenue officer <b>Elizabet=
h</b> <b>Herbst</b>-<b>Brady</b> will host her first revenue summit, which =
I=E2=80=99m told was whittled down from two days to one day by Herbst-Brady=
, herself. (I heard that she even thought of canceling it altogether). Reme=
mber that Herbst-Brady is overseeing both advertising <i>and </i>consumer r=
evenue=E2=80=94a step up from her longtime predecessor, <b>Pamela</b> <b>Dr=
ucker</b> <b>Mann</b>, who didn=E2=80=99t touch the consumer business, incl=
uding subscriptions. The change makes sense, and was the right move on Lync=
h=E2=80=99s part: Every revenue stream should work hand-in-hand, and should=
 ladder up to one person. The problem, of course, is that the new strategy =
probably requires significant streamlining=E2=80=94another <i>restructuring=
</i>, as Duncan would say. We all know what that means. Soon enough, one su=
spects, many Cond=C3=A9 employees will be
compelled into action by the more immediate need to fight for their jobs. L=
ynch has promised no more layoffs this year, but 2025 is less than three mo=
nths away. <br/><br/>Regardless, it=E2=80=99s clear that Lynch=E2=80=99s le=
adership team will have to manage a two-front challenge. Last Friday, in on=
e of the company=E2=80=99s employee resource groups on Slack (I thank my lu=
cky stars every day that we=E2=80=99re not big enough to have those yet), a=
 <i>Vanity Fair </i>fact-checker ruffled feathers by suggesting that the co=
mpany create a Palestinian working group to educate employees on how to be =
=E2=80=9Cantiracist.=E2=80=9D Many people in the group felt this comment wa=
s inappropriate, especially for a fact-checker, who is supposed to be impar=
tial. What=E2=80=99s more, there were implications that such a =E2=80=9Cwor=
king group=E2=80=9D would, by definition, be antisemitic. If only they had =
a D.E.I. officer to handle it all.<br/></td>
